y Churchyard, Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England":"Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England","Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England":"Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"January 1519–31 January 1600":"January 1519–31 January 1600","1519–1600":"1519–1600","1518–1551":"1518–1551","1529–1597":"1529–1597","1547–1619":"1547–1619","1492–Male":"1492–Deceased","January 1519":"January 1519","before 20 April 1597":"before 20 April 1597","1571":"1571","1492":"1492","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1600":"1600","31 January 1600":"31 January 1600","about 1547":"about 1547","1587":"1587","1597":"1597","1585":"1585","1551":"1551","about 1543":"about 1543","after 31 January 1600":"after 31 January 1600","about 1552":"about 1552","1619":"1619","1519":"1519","1529":"1529","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary Churchyard, Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England":"Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England","Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England":"Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tylney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Tilney (Norfolk), which derives its name from the Old English personal name <i>Tila</i>, <i>Tilla</i> (genitive <i>Tilan</i>, <i>Tillan</i>) + Old English <i>ēg</i> ‘island’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":30,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":39,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":50,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":52,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":66,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":68,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Tylney was born in January 1519, in Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England as the daughter of John Tylney. She married Richard Greneway about 1543, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 31 January 1600, in her hometown, at the age of 81, and was buried in Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England."},"et":{"January 1519–31 January 1600":"jaanuar 1519–31. jaanuar 1600","1519–1600":"1519–1600","1518–1551":"1518–1551","1529–1597":"1529–1597","1547–1619":"1547–1619","1492–Male":"1492–Surnud","January 1519":"jaanuar 1519","before 20 April 1597":"enne 20. aprilli 1597","1571":"1571","1492":"1492","1569":"1569"